2016 Presidential Campaign - FEC Database Individual Contribution Analysis

Data Description

This data comes from the Federal Election Commissions Contributor data from all states, found here: http://fec.gov/disclosurep/PDownload.do

This list only includes contributions from individuals and does not include receipts from other sources. The data also only reflects the early part of the race, with no data included past 9/30/2015.

Descriptive Univariate Graphs

I first created a barchart showing the amount raised by each candiate to get a sense of the data. Hillary has riased far more money as counted by this dataset. She is dominating rest of the field with over $60,000,000 raised. The next closest is Jeb Bush with over $20 Milllion raised.

A summary of the total contriubtion. Note that Hilarys Total is 20 x the median.

I decided to look into the cumulative sum of the candidates contributions to see if I could find anything interesting. My first graph looks at Hilary alone. Hilary shows steady increase in funds, there are no huge leaps or flat areas which are immediately obvious.

Here is the graph of the top 8 candidates over time. Interestingly there is not much of an obvious distinction between the candidates trends.

Retired Contributions Analysis Graphs

This graph shows retired contribtions per candidate. Hilary is again in the lead. However, it is important to note that she also has the highest total contribution amount, so she might not have the highest proportion of retired contriubtions.

This graph shows the portion of retired persons who make up their total contriubtion base. Ben Carson has the highest portion with almost 30% of his contributions coming from retired persons. Donald Trump and Carly Fiorina are next at above 25% of the total contriubtions coming from retired persons

I want to test whether there is a relationship between the percent of income from retired persons and Total_contriubtions. To do this I make a scatter plot with Total contriubtions and a regression line.

Here is the Summary of the correlation. As we can see the RSquared value is .001371477 which is very weak.

Location Correlation Analysis

First I want to study Washington D.Cs funding correlation with overall funding. Like the retired plot I made a bar graph showing the percent of contribution total which comes from Washington D.C

I created a graph that looks at the percent of contributions from DC with the total donations overall

There looks to be a stronger correlation with percent of contriubtions from Washignton DC then with retired persons, with every extra .01 % from Washington DC leading to an expected increase of around $7M in total contributions. The R Squared here is not too high, but is not weak enough to be dicounted completely:

## [1] 0.4421663

Now I will try to see DCs correlation compared with States and Cities. First, here is a scatter plot showing what percent of each candidates money comes from every state. For instance, 60% of Chris Christies money comes from his native New Jersey, as indicated by the larger dot. I limited the data to state values which make over 1.5% of the value for that candidate to help filter out the less relevant variables.

Here we can see that the DC area funding correlates more with overall candidate funding then any other State/Region which would make sense as it is the center of politics in the United States I limited the values shown to RSquared values over .05.

However, DC is a city as well as a district, so influence is more concentrated then with States.Below is a graph showing which Cities give to which candidates. For simplicity and processing, I limited the cities to the top 75 cities by number of donations. Also, as I did with the states, I limited the threshold of the data to cities which are over 1.5% of any candidates total contributions.

Here is a graph of the RSquared data for each city. Washington DC still shows the highest R Squared value. Surprisingly to me, Mineapolis is the second highest.

I want to further narrow down which areas correlate the most with overall funding, so I will now repeat the process but with Zip Codes. Here is a scatter plot. I made the cut to be counted as .5% rather then 1.5% because Zip Codes are smaller and naturally will make a smaller part of the Total Contributions. For some context 10024 is the Zip Code for the upper West Side in Manhattan. 77024 is a Zip Code in Houston, two miles away from where Ted Cruz went to High School.

Here are the r-scores of the top districts in terms of correlation. The results are much more siginificant then the city or state data, with the top r^2 value reacing over .7. For context, the top score, Zip Code: 60614 is the Lincoln Park area of Chicago and which contains Dupont University. 20009 is a Zip Code minutes near the Washington DC Mall. 90046 is the Zip Code for West Hollywood and the Hollywood hills, 90069 is the Zip Code right next door on the sunset strip. 10128, is the Zip Code for the Carneige Hill area of Manhatten.

These places are all very wealthy, liberal and often culturally important areas. This would make sense as wealthy Democrats are more likely to live in large cities, and have their wealth concentrated into a few Zip Codes. Republican wealth is more likely to be spread over several Zip Codes. As a result we would expect to find that the Democrats who capture these key areas are likely to have a larger overall base of financial support.

These next two graphs show the total value of the contributions from 60614, then the portion of the candidates total that are from 60614.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One:

Description One:

Plot one shows the percent of a candidates Total_contribution which comes from each particular state. You can see that the generally the less popular candiadtes generally have contributions coming from mostly there home state(eg. Bobby Jindal has 80% of his contributions coming from Louisianas does George Pataki % from New York). Candidates with larger total contriubitons have a more diversified base of support. For instance Hilary has significant portions of revenue (defined as over 2.5% of her total) coming from 15 states.

Looking at the states, Florida and California are the only states to contribute over 2.5% of every candidates Total Contriubtions, which makes some sense as these states are very populous. It is interesting to note however, that both Florida and Califonia do not provide over 20% of any candidates total contributions.

Plot Two:

Description Two:

This graph shows the Coefficient of determination or R Squared Score betweeen contributions for a candidate which come from that particular city, and the Total_contriubitons overall. In other words this score shows the proportion of the differences in the Total Contributions for each candidate, which can be predicted by the percentage of Total Contriubtions each candidate gets from the respective city.

Washington DC unsurprisingly has the highest Rsquared value, which makes sense given the fact that DC is the seat of American politics. Minneapolis is second for less clear reasons. Surprisingly New York barely makes the .05 threshold for appearing on the graph. The inclusion of Salt Lake City at a .16 value is logical as it is the center for the Mormon Faith, and would most likely be a good indicator of the contribtions of the entire Mormon community. One city that is included, Coral Gables at .15, does not make sense if you did not know it was very close suburb to Miami.

Plot Three:

Description Three:

This graph shows the top 8 eight candidates by there campaign contributions over time. The jump on July 1 was due to the end of the campaign rebate program,which showed up in my data as negative total_contriubitons. This had been depressing the overall campaign contributions of many of the canidates significantly. Most notably was Jeb Bush who saw a jump of around $4 Million Dollars as a result of the rebate program.

Also interesting is the jump that many candidates reciever (around $1-3Million each) at the end of the October. I am not sure why this is the case, but I would guess that it has something to do with the end of the fiscal year which occurs in October. Also intereting to me is the bump that Ted Cruz experiences around the first of April. Ben Carson is the only other candidate who is active in the race at that point and he had raised very little at that point. As a result it is hard to tell whether that bump is a result of something Ted Cruz did, or something procedural. I would guess however, that is procedural phenomenon, like the end of the fiscal year bump, because it occurs exactly at the half-way point of the fiscal year.

Reflections:

The data provided many intriguing insights on the election and election funding. The first is that Hilary is dominating in the democratic polls for a reason. She has taken far more money in then any other candidate, and that should really help her hold off Bernie Sanders and help tremendously with the genereal election as well.

It was also interesting that the candidates with the highest level of retired support were the three outisiders on the republican side, Carly Fiorina, Donald Trump and Ben Carson. This could possibly indicate that retired persons are likely very disastisfied with the Republican establishment, as these three candidates are not establishment republicans and are classified as outsiders.

I thought the location analysis was especially interesting. The fact that Washington DCs funding correlated highly with total funding made a lot of sense. It was interesting to see that as a whole NYCs, but that one of its Zip Codes was.

In the future I would like to compare the correlation of the funding totals of different locations on Republicans and Democrats sepearte total funding numbers. I would also like to look at which jobs are the most influential, and map rSquared values as I did with location. I would also like to map the infulence of these locations and jobs on actuall poll numbers and votes, not just overall contriubtions.

It is important to note that these amounts only cover the money going to the candidates themselves. The candidates also have super-pacs which they are not officially allowed to control. These superpacs are allowed to take unlimited amount of campaign contributions and as a result often have even more money then the individual campaigns.
